Remarks. This seemingly rare species is usually characterized by its large, reddish shell, with strong rounded spiral cords and coarse nodulose sculpture starting on the teleoconch, but usually restricted to the first 3–4 whorls ( Marini 1975 ). The species, in fact, attains a larger size than reported in the original description (H=6.9, D=7.0 mm) and followed by the literature (e.g., Rios 1994 , 2009 ;
Rosenberg et al. 2009
), reaching a shell height of 10.9 mm (MZSP 67303) and a maximum diameter of 10.8 mm (MZSP 36037) in non-MD 55 specimens we analyzed (from Canopus Bank, off northeastern Brazil ).
